onary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Harley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from either of two places called Harley (Shropshire, Yorkshire). The Shropshire placename derives from Old English <i>hær</i> ‘rock, heap of stones’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. The Yorkshire placename derives from Old English <i>hara</i> ‘hare’ or <i>hær</i> + <i>hlāw</i> ‘mound, hill’, later replaced by <i>lēah</i>.","Irish (Donegal): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hEarghaile</b> ‘descendant of <i>Earghal</i>’, a variant of the personal name <i>Fearghal</i> without the initial <i>F-</i>. This name has also become   Herley   and   Hurley  . Compare   Arrell   and   Harrell  .","Scottish (Fife): habitational name from any of several places called Harlaw in Midlothian, Peeblesshire, and Berwickshire, named in Older Scots with <i>hare</i> ‘gray’ + <i>law</i> ‘hill’."],"variants":[{"name":"Herley","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Art, Cormac.","Irish: variant of   Hurley  , probably via   Herlihy  .","English: variant of   Harley   or   Hurley  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":30,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":55,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":68,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret de Harley was born about 1260, in Leominster, Herefordshire, England. She had at least 1 son with John Parker."},"et":{"about 1260–":"umbes 1260–Surnud","1256–Male":"1256–Surnud","1284–Male":"1284–Surnud","1260–Female":"1260–Surnud","about 1260":"umbes 1260","1315":"1315","1256":"1256","1284":"1284","1260":"1260","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"England","Leominster, Herefordshire, England":"Leominster, Herefordshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1260–":"noin 1260–Kuollut","1256–Male":"1256–Kuollut","1284–Male":"1284–Kuollut","1260–Female":"1260–Kuollut","about 1260":"noin 1260","1315":"1315","1256":"1256","1284":"1284","1260":"1260","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"England","Leominster, Herefordshire, England":"Leominster, Herefordshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1260–":"environ 1260–Décédée","1256–Male":"1256–Décédé","1284–Male":"1284–Décédé","1260–Femal